Python Intro

What is Python?
Python is a popular high-level language. It was created by Guido van Rossum and first released in 1991.

Typical uses:
- Web development (server-side)
- Automation and scripting
- Data analysis and science
- Desktop tools and general software

Why Python?
- Runs on Windows, macOS, Linux, and more
- Readable syntax, often fewer lines than lower-level languages
- Large standard library and community packages
- You can write procedural, object-oriented, or functional style code

Good to know
- This course uses Python 3 (the current line; Python 2 is retired).
- You can edit .py files in any text editor; IDEs (VS Code, PyCharm, Thonny, etc.) help with larger projects.
- Python uses new lines to end statements (no required semicolons).
- Indentation (spaces) defines blocks (if, loops, functions, classes)—not curly braces.

Official download: https://www.python.org/downloads/

See also: https://www.w3schools.com/python/python_intro.asp

